{
  "answer": "In Manusmṛti Book 1, the *varṇas* (social classes) emerge cosmogonically from the body of the creator as part of the primordial ordering of the universe: \"And for the sake of the prosperity of the worlds, he caused the Brahmana, the Kshatriya, the Vaishya, and the Shudra to emanate from his mouth, arms, thighs, and feet.\"[^1] This Puruṣa-like origin ties social hierarchy directly to cosmic creation, with each *varṇa*'s innate qualities and duties flowing from its bodily source.[^2]\n\nSlokāntara echoes this framework almost verbatim in its gnomic exposition, deriving the four *varṇas* from Brahmā's body (Brāhmaṇa from the forehead/mouth-area, Kṣatriya from the arms, Vaiśya from the thighs, Śūdra from the feet), but shifts to pragmatic duties suited to a Javanese agrarian and mercantile context: Vaiśyas as farmers and herdsmen who \"care for the land, ... work dry fields and wet rice fields, ... [and] produce the food of the world,\" while Śūdras are traders focused on \"buying and selling ... to trade, to sail, to lend and to borrow.\"[^3] Brāhmaṇas perform rituals and study scriptures; Kṣatriyas wage war and protect.[^4]\n\nSlokāntara clearly presupposes Manu's cosmogonic framework—it replicates the body-part schema to legitimize hierarchy—but adapts it pragmatically: duties emphasize local roles (e.g., rice farming over Vedic cattle-herding for Vaiśyas; maritime trade for Śūdras) amid warnings of chaos if *varṇas* neglect them, rather than dwelling on metaphysical origins.[^5]\n\n[^1]: Manusmṛti, [Chapter 1, paragraph p-13a2db](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/01/translation/#p-13a2db).\n[^2]: Manusmṛti, [Chapter 1, paragraph p-1c4c70](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/01/translation/#p-1c4c70).\n[^3]: Slokāntara, [Chapter 1, paragraphs p-86d937 to p-0130ba](/works/unknown-slokantara-d7a628/01/translation/#p-86d937); Slokāntara, [Chapter 1, paragraphs p-428c5c and p-605381](/works/unknown-slokantara-d7a628/01/translation/#p-428c5c).\n[^4]: Slokāntara, [Chapter 1, paragraphs p-86d937 to p-0130ba](/works/unknown-slokantara-d7a628/01/translation/#p-86d937).\n[^5]: Slokāntara, [Chapter 1, paragraph p-0130ba](/works/unknown-slokantara-d7a628/01/translation/#p-0130ba).",
